00:05:39,768 --> 00:05:41,330
and face its own challenges.

102
00:05:41,330 --> 00:05:43,011
Art can do the same, audio, writing.

103
00:05:43,011 --> 00:05:45,012
But if you trace them back far enough,

104
00:05:45,012 --> 00:05:46,813
they all share an ancestry.

105
00:05:46,813 --> 00:05:49,595
Which I think, looking at the project this way,

106
00:05:49,595 --> 00:05:52,277
gave us a really great place to start.

107
00:05:52,277 --> 00:05:54,439
And no matter what challenges we face later,

108
00:05:54,439 --> 00:05:58,021
we can always come back to this trunk that we built.

109
00:05:59,395 --> 00:06:04,431
sort of a clearly defined and articulated vision statement for the game.

110
00:06:06,280 --> 00:06:08,922
We did this a couple of different ways.

111
00:06:08,922 --> 00:06:10,823
The old collect a bunch of reference art,

112
00:06:10,823 --> 00:06:15,626
put it on an image, classic, classic move.

113
00:06:15,626 --> 00:06:19,288
But putting, like annotating it with what about those images

114
00:06:19,288 --> 00:06:21,669
is really important, I think, because it's not enough just

115
00:06:21,669 --> 00:06:23,771
to stick a picture somewhere.

116
00:06:23,771 --> 00:06:25,332
We had a lot of conversation and debate.

117
00:06:25,332 --> 00:06:28,834
We stress tested what we felt like the game would be about

118
00:06:28,834 --> 00:06:31,355
and how the game would handle certain problems

119
00:06:31,355 --> 00:06:32,336
as they popped up.

120
00:06:32,336 --> 00:06:33,457
And we ended up with this.

121
00:06:33,617 --> 00:06:36,859
uncompromising, gothic rogue-like, low fantasy,

122
00:06:36,859 --> 00:06:41,282
Lovecraftian adventure that challenges players to make the

123
00:06:41,282 --> 00:06:44,984
best of a bad situation and make decisions with permanent

124
00:06:44,984 --> 00:06:48,367
consequences with imperfect information. And that really

125
00:06:48,367 --> 00:06:51,769
became the sort of core vision for the game and everything was

126
00:06:51,769 --> 00:06:52,630
routed through that.

127
00:06:53,725 --> 00:06:57,428
And I wanted to point out I think the love child metaphor.

128
00:06:57,428 --> 00:07:00,291
Thanks Jeff for clarifying what that actually is.

129
00:07:00,291 --> 00:07:01,491
You know when you're like,

130
00:07:01,491 --> 00:07:03,613
oh my game is X meets Y.

131
00:07:03,613 --> 00:07:05,855
For us it became like XCOM meets Dark Souls.

132
00:07:05,855 --> 00:07:07,937
I think that's nice to arrive at at the end of the day

133
00:07:07,937 --> 00:07:10,499
after you've gone through a more exhaustive process

134
00:07:10,499 --> 00:07:12,400
of understanding what it is you're trying to make.

135
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:14,962
But if you start from there, I think it's really reductive.

136
00:07:14,962 --> 00:07:15,963
And I think that you risk,

137
00:07:15,963 --> 00:07:17,984
like if that's your internal mantra

138
00:07:17,984 --> 00:07:19,005
is XCOM meets Dark Souls.

139
00:07:19,305 --> 00:07:23,468
It's not specific enough because you're not saying what about XCOM you're taking and leaving

140
00:07:23,468 --> 00:07:26,230
and what about Dark Souls you're taking and leaving.

141
00:07:26,230 --> 00:07:28,712
It's just up to personal interpretation.

142
00:07:28,712 --> 00:07:34,155
And I guess that's what I'm really driving at is that when you settle on a creative direction

143
00:07:34,155 --> 00:07:36,697
for your game, it cannot be subject to a personal interpretation.

144
00:07:36,697 --> 00:07:38,698
It needs to be strong enough to exist on its own.

145
00:07:38,698 --> 00:07:40,059
So I did this drawing of Batman.

146
00:07:43,085 --> 00:07:45,489
I think what worked really well for us

147
00:07:45,489 --> 00:07:47,613
by defining this vision for the game,

148
00:07:47,613 --> 00:07:50,397
repeatedly articulating it, and actively looking

149
00:07:50,397 --> 00:07:53,442
for ways to involve it in our development process,

150
00:07:53,442 --> 00:07:55,566
it kind of became its own.

151
00:07:56,517 --> 00:08:00,021
entity. We externalized it. Darkest Dungeon became a team

152
00:08:00,021 --> 00:08:04,265
member. It wasn't what I thought was cool or what Tyler thought

153
00:08:04,265 --> 00:08:08,109
would work. The game was a part of our team. And it had its own

154
00:08:08,109 --> 00:08:10,291
likes and dislikes and things that it wanted to be and things

155
00:08:10,291 --> 00:08:12,934
that it didn't need. Like parkour.

156
00:08:13,729 --> 00:08:16,910
So it's a lot like Batman and Bruce Wayne.

157
00:08:16,910 --> 00:08:20,211
The creative director is a man, or a woman, obviously.

158
00:08:20,211 --> 00:08:24,813
You can be sort of swayed by shifting trends.

159
00:08:24,813 --> 00:08:28,535
You can wake up one morning after you play a great round

160
00:08:28,535 --> 00:08:30,556
of Fallout 4, and now you want to have power armor in your

161
00:08:30,556 --> 00:08:32,016
racing game.

162
00:08:32,016 --> 00:08:34,998
You're vulnerable to these things as a person, just by

163
00:08:34,998 --> 00:08:36,919
the nature of, especially a creative person, right?

164
00:08:36,919 --> 00:08:38,839
We're very easily attracted to neat ideas.

165
00:08:39,460 --> 00:08:42,501
But the creative direction for a game has to be a symbol.

166
00:08:42,501 --> 00:08:45,462
It has to be immutable and powerful

167
00:08:45,462 --> 00:08:46,682
and outside of yourself.

168
00:08:46,682 --> 00:08:49,123
And Batman's really cool.

169
00:08:49,123 --> 00:08:50,884
I could have chosen a different superhero,

170
00:08:50,884 --> 00:08:53,545
but it wouldn't have been a great creative choice given

171
00:08:53,545 --> 00:08:55,405
the talk, subject matter.

172
00:08:55,405 --> 00:08:56,966
So yeah, essentially, the thing has

173
00:08:56,966 --> 00:08:58,846
to be strong enough to live on its own and fight crime.

174
00:09:01,327 --> 00:09:04,708
So being, you know, moving into production with the confidence

175
00:09:04,708 --> 00:09:07,909
of what we knew what we wanted to make led to some really

176
00:09:07,909 --> 00:09:09,749
interesting choices. So what I thought I would do is

177
00:09:09,749 --> 00:09:12,450
demonstrate the practical application of creative

178
00:09:12,450 --> 00:09:14,890
direction by just sort of selecting a few sort of key

179
00:09:14,890 --> 00:09:17,391
examples. Like I said, it was literally something we talked

180
00:09:17,391 --> 00:09:18,852
about all the time. But

181
00:09:19,870 --> 00:09:24,818
the art style, the overall presentation of the game, the

182
00:09:24,818 --> 00:09:27,423
writing style and the lore, some marketing, some game design

183
00:09:27,423 --> 00:09:30,808
stuff. All of these things were really like big sort of home

184
00:09:30,808 --> 00:09:33,833
runs I think for our creative direction. Excuse me.

185
00:09:37,896 --> 00:09:40,357
When we first started, pixel art was hot,

186
00:09:40,357 --> 00:09:41,598
and it was only getting hotter,

187
00:09:41,598 --> 00:09:43,099
and you could get a lot of attention

188
00:09:43,099 --> 00:09:46,460
by virtue of simply being a pixel art game.

189
00:09:46,460 --> 00:09:48,861
And I think there's a case to be made

190
00:09:48,861 --> 00:09:50,882
for the irony of cute pixel characters

191
00:09:50,882 --> 00:09:54,364
suffering horrible depression and syphilis in a dungeon.

192
00:09:54,364 --> 00:09:55,505
Like, that's kind of funny, right?

193
00:09:55,505 --> 00:09:57,926
There's something there.

194
00:09:58,895 --> 00:10:01,557
It, ultimately we looked at it,

195
00:10:01,557 --> 00:10:03,778
but it communicated the wrong things.

196
00:10:03,778 --> 00:10:06,140
It led out with this idea of retro and charming.

197
00:10:06,140 --> 00:10:08,522
And even though we were sort of a retro inspired

198
00:10:08,522 --> 00:10:11,765
kind of RPG, we couldn't lead out with that

199
00:10:11,765 --> 00:10:13,586
rose colored nostalgia and cuteness.

200
00:10:13,586 --> 00:10:16,468
It actually, it flew in the face

201
00:10:16,468 --> 00:10:18,710
of what we were trying to accomplish.

202
00:10:18,710 --> 00:10:21,532
We needed something like really awful and depressing

203
00:10:21,532 --> 00:10:25,375
to really just hammer that horrible stuff home.

204
00:10:27,164 --> 00:10:29,226
So heavy blacks came into play.

205
00:10:29,226 --> 00:10:31,408
We started looking at a lot of comic books

206
00:10:31,408 --> 00:10:33,690
and how to deliver on that vibe.

207
00:10:33,690 --> 00:10:37,333
And the looseness of the art really reinforced

208
00:10:37,333 --> 00:10:38,314
this idea of imperfection.

209
00:10:38,314 --> 00:10:39,616
Your heroes are imperfect.

210
00:10:39,616 --> 00:10:42,198
The information you're getting for your decision-making

211
00:10:42,198 --> 00:10:43,039
is imperfect.

212
00:10:43,039 --> 00:10:45,201
Imperfection is a huge theme in our game.

213
00:10:45,501 --> 00:10:48,344
and it was great to give that like a visual personification

214
00:10:48,344 --> 00:10:49,665
so that it's literally there.

215
00:10:49,665 --> 00:10:51,186
Even if you're not consciously aware of it

216
00:10:51,186 --> 00:10:53,568
when you're playing, it's one of those things

217
00:10:53,568 --> 00:10:55,410
that it creeps up on you and you understand it

218
00:10:55,410 --> 00:10:57,772
without necessarily knowing it consciously.

219
00:10:57,772 --> 00:10:59,853
So I think that was a good choice.

220
00:10:59,853 --> 00:11:04,958
And the big win for me is that if I can be loose and sloppy

221
00:11:04,958 --> 00:11:06,619
and people still think it's cool,

222
00:11:06,619 --> 00:11:10,602
then I can get more done faster, which is great.

223
00:11:10,602 --> 00:11:11,663
Because there's only one of me.

224
00:11:13,237 --> 00:11:17,800
The other sort of assumption when you go in to make like an

225
00:11:17,800 --> 00:11:22,723
RPG especially a turn based one is that the top down ISO Diablo

226
00:11:22,723 --> 00:11:26,446
or classic Final Fantasy grid cam is usually the default

227
00:11:26,446 --> 00:11:28,867
assumption when you describe a game like this to someone. But

228
00:11:28,867 --> 00:11:31,529
we ended up with this weird side scrolling thing. You're always

229
00:11:31,529 --> 00:11:35,132
moving left to right. And the reason was because as you can

230
00:11:35,132 --> 00:11:37,954
see we did some exploration. Even after sort of getting some

231
00:11:37,954 --> 00:11:40,655
real solid wins on the art style you can see it's starting to

232
00:11:40,655 --> 00:11:41,956
creep in over there.

233
00:11:42,637 --> 00:11:45,698
we tried to make it work with this sort of,

234
00:11:45,698 --> 00:11:48,318
operating under the assumption that we had to do this.

235
00:11:48,318 --> 00:11:49,439
But the more we got into it,

236
00:11:49,439 --> 00:11:52,020
we realized that the wide angles

237
00:11:52,020 --> 00:11:54,721
and the sort of godlike overview

238
00:11:54,721 --> 00:11:56,981
robbed the game of that claustrophobic tension

239
00:11:56,981 --> 00:11:58,562
that we felt like was so important.

240
00:11:58,562 --> 00:12:00,903
We wanted you down in the dungeon with your characters.

241
00:12:00,903 --> 00:12:03,103
We don't want you standing up above like,

242
00:12:03,103 --> 00:12:05,404
you know, the Lord, kind of looking down

243
00:12:05,404 --> 00:12:07,525
with this wide panoramic view.

244
00:12:08,725 --> 00:12:11,146
It lost its sense of intimacy and a lot of the intensity.

245
00:12:11,146 --> 00:12:14,987
And also, our game is about the psychological ramifications

246
00:12:14,987 --> 00:12:16,967
of adventuring, and that's the characters.

247
00:12:16,967 --> 00:12:18,308
It's not the environment.

248
00:12:18,308 --> 00:12:20,048
So it's less about dungeon layout

249
00:12:20,048 --> 00:12:21,989
and more about who's in the dungeon.

250
00:12:21,989 --> 00:12:23,949
So again, that was an argument to be made

251
00:12:23,949 --> 00:12:26,650
for getting nice, close in on those characters.

252
00:12:26,650 --> 00:12:27,970
And it's also really hard to relate

253
00:12:27,970 --> 00:12:28,870
to the top of someone's head.

254
00:12:28,870 --> 00:12:31,291
So, you know, having nice side view characters

255
00:12:31,291 --> 00:12:32,811
gives you something that's a little bit more interesting

256
00:12:32,811 --> 00:12:34,492
to look at, and you can kind of attach yourself

257
00:12:34,492 --> 00:12:35,732
to the look and feel of the character.

258
00:12:36,308 --> 00:12:38,311
And again, another big win is that it's the same set

259
00:12:38,311 --> 00:12:40,615
of assets as combat.

260
00:12:40,615 --> 00:12:44,040
So we didn't have to JRPG to a battle cam and, again,

261
00:12:44,040 --> 00:12:46,223
imply bigger spaces.

262
00:12:46,223 --> 00:12:47,806
And as a result, the game feels very,

263
00:12:47,806 --> 00:12:51,291
you're very wrapped up in it as you're playing it.

264
00:12:54,657 --> 00:12:58,119
The writing, a big assumption I think too

265
00:12:58,119 --> 00:13:00,300
that we sort of wrestled with is that

266
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:02,801
when you make an RPG, usually there's gotta be

267
00:13:02,801 --> 00:13:04,882
dwarves and elves that thought 10,000 years ago

268
00:13:04,882 --> 00:13:07,003
and then there's a chosen one thrown in there at some point.

269
00:13:07,003 --> 00:13:08,484
Maybe there's a life tree, I don't know.

270
00:13:08,484 --> 00:13:10,305
Collect a few elements.

271
00:13:10,305 --> 00:13:13,747
But it's always very exhaustively spelled out

272
00:13:13,747 --> 00:13:16,288
and quite frankly, it kinda bores me to tears sometimes

273
00:13:16,288 --> 00:13:17,809
and I kinda skip through a lot of the quests.

274
00:13:17,809 --> 00:13:19,910
I'm like, do you want the wolf pelts?

275
00:13:19,910 --> 00:13:21,771
Yes or no?

276
00:13:21,771 --> 00:13:24,292
I just wanna get another sword, man.

277
00:13:25,340 --> 00:13:27,229
So we felt like for our game though, um...

278
00:13:29,191 --> 00:13:32,572
imperfect information. We don't want to spell out the story. We

279
00:13:32,572 --> 00:13:37,113
want to suggest it's there and create this fog around the

280
00:13:37,113 --> 00:13:41,653
player to deliver on this twilight zone uncertainty that I

281
00:13:41,653 --> 00:13:44,654
think is really important and it features in a lot of love craft

282
00:13:44,654 --> 00:13:47,515
stuff. You only get a keyhole glimpse into these awful

283
00:13:47,515 --> 00:13:50,875
horrors and if they were to be described exactly it does them a

284
00:13:50,875 --> 00:13:56,056
disservice. So we went a different direction. We tried to

285
00:13:56,056 --> 00:13:56,616
tell the story.

286
00:13:57,632 --> 00:13:59,452
as much in the panels as in the gutters.

287
00:13:59,452 --> 00:14:01,634
Like, I'm sure a lot of you guys read comics,

288
00:14:01,634 --> 00:14:03,174
and your brain interpolates what's

289
00:14:03,174 --> 00:14:05,555
happening between the panels in the white space in between.

290
00:14:05,555 --> 00:14:09,837
And so that gives you a point of contact

291
00:14:09,837 --> 00:14:12,719
as the consumer of the product to get invested,

292
00:14:12,719 --> 00:14:15,520
to use your own imagination to fill in those gaps.

293
00:14:15,520 --> 00:14:17,581
And we felt like that would be, it

294
00:14:17,581 --> 00:14:19,882
would pair nicely with the comic book style art,

295
00:14:19,882 --> 00:14:23,164
and it would allow people to sort of integrate themselves

296
00:14:23,164 --> 00:14:23,884
into the fiction.

297
00:14:24,447 --> 00:14:26,828
And it means that we don't have to write a novel, which

298
00:14:26,828 --> 00:14:27,508
is a huge win.

299
00:14:27,508 --> 00:14:31,830
The writing style was a big risk for us as well,

300
00:14:31,830 --> 00:14:36,392
because the game uses a lot of really antiquated verbiage,

301
00:14:36,392 --> 00:14:37,992
if you will.

302
00:14:37,992 --> 00:14:41,714
And it was really a way of us honoring the source material.

303
00:14:41,714 --> 00:14:43,754
We felt like we couldn't decouple

304
00:14:43,754 --> 00:14:48,736
the Lovecraftian overwrought tonality from the actual.

305
00:14:49,237 --> 00:14:53,138
thematic influences. I felt like they were really enmeshed.

306
00:14:53,138 --> 00:14:56,440
And so to try and tell a Lovecraft style story without

307
00:14:56,440 --> 00:15:00,802
that terminology, that phrasing, that turn of phrase, would rob

308
00:15:00,802 --> 00:15:04,644
it of something inherently that it needed. But it was a risk as

309
00:15:04,644 --> 00:15:08,906
far as localization goes. And we were worried that people just

310
00:15:08,906 --> 00:15:12,288
wouldn't like it or wouldn't get it. But that was a risk we were

311
00:15:12,288 --> 00:15:14,409
willing to take because we felt like it honored the creative

312
00:15:14,409 --> 00:15:15,830
direction of the game much more.

313
00:15:16,826 --> 00:15:20,411
And again, yeah, horror thrives in the absence of certainty.

314
00:15:20,411 --> 00:15:22,454
So the dark places of your imagination,

315
00:15:22,454 --> 00:15:24,557
that's where kind of fear and concern settle in.

316
00:15:24,557 --> 00:15:26,981
And anytime you can pay that out in a horror game,

317
00:15:26,981 --> 00:15:28,843
I think you're doing well.

318
00:15:30,667 --> 00:15:34,529
So we've looked at a few of these soft science areas

319
00:15:34,529 --> 00:15:36,171
where the creative direction was important.

320
00:15:36,171 --> 00:15:37,291
That's kind of low-hanging fruit,

321
00:15:37,291 --> 00:15:39,193
because I think when people talk about creative direction,

322
00:15:39,193 --> 00:15:40,954
they immediately associate it with art

323
00:15:40,954 --> 00:15:42,655
and that kind of thing.

324
00:15:42,655 --> 00:15:44,497
But we used it actually as a razor

325
00:15:44,497 --> 00:15:47,339
when it came to features as well.

326
00:15:47,339 --> 00:15:52,002
We really tried to ask the game essentially what it wanted,

327
00:15:52,002 --> 00:15:54,384
what it needed to be able to pay off its identity.

328
00:15:55,224 --> 00:15:58,866
So for instance, a gear system is a popular thing

329
00:15:58,866 --> 00:15:59,526
to have in an RPG.

330
00:15:59,526 --> 00:16:01,447
It's usually what drives the player experience.

331
00:16:01,447 --> 00:16:03,928
They want to upgrade their stuff and get new loot.

332
00:16:03,928 --> 00:16:07,909
But it's extremely, extremely costly.

333
00:16:07,909 --> 00:16:11,771
And we have a small team, obviously, and limited resources.

334
00:16:11,771 --> 00:16:13,051
And we had to really ask ourselves,

335
00:16:13,051 --> 00:16:15,052
is this something, is this a road we want to go down?

336
00:16:15,052 --> 00:16:17,933
Does this actually serve the creative direction of the game?

337
00:16:17,933 --> 00:16:19,174
And the answer was no.

338
00:16:19,174 --> 00:16:21,675
Our game is about the sword arm, not the sword.

339
00:16:22,025 --> 00:16:25,528
It's about the person who's wearing the armor,

340
00:16:25,528 --> 00:16:27,849
not a number of upgrade gems on the armor.

341
00:16:27,849 --> 00:16:28,670
Those games are great.

342
00:16:28,670 --> 00:16:29,691
I love those games.

343
00:16:29,691 --> 00:16:31,292
But that's not this game.

344
00:16:31,292 --> 00:16:33,774
And I think understanding what game we were making

345
00:16:33,774 --> 00:16:35,716
really helped us make these decisions

346
00:16:35,716 --> 00:16:37,958
and really never look back.

347
00:16:37,958 --> 00:16:39,359
So we used it as a razor to measure

348
00:16:39,359 --> 00:16:41,921
the relative value and importance of many, many features.

349
00:16:41,921 --> 00:16:44,203
You'll notice there's no crafting system.

350
00:16:46,001 --> 00:16:49,084
we reduced it down to like two inventory slots,

351
00:16:49,084 --> 00:16:51,345
but then we blew out the number of items that were there

352
00:16:51,345 --> 00:16:53,627
because we recognized the value

353
00:16:53,627 --> 00:16:54,648
in having collectible loot.

354
00:16:54,648 --> 00:16:56,730
It's great, it's part and parcel of the experience,

355
00:16:56,730 --> 00:16:58,692
but it shouldn't play lead guitar in this game.

356
00:16:58,692 --> 00:17:00,533
It's the bass or even just the little dude

357
00:17:00,533 --> 00:17:02,135
with the shaker in the back, you know?

358
00:17:05,099 --> 00:17:09,242
It applies to marketing too. Trailers, when we were first

359
00:17:09,242 --> 00:17:13,805
getting started I did a lot of research into sort of how game

360
00:17:13,805 --> 00:17:16,386
trailers should be constructed and the conventional wisdom was

361
00:17:16,386 --> 00:17:18,768
that they need to be fast, punchy, there needs to be flying

362
00:17:18,768 --> 00:17:22,350
text. I think you're supposed to announce a new game mechanic

363
00:17:22,350 --> 00:17:26,593
every five seconds. It's all, you can find it on Google. We

364
00:17:26,593 --> 00:17:30,935
didn't do any of that. Just because it didn't align with the

365
00:17:30,935 --> 00:17:33,397
mood and tone of the game. So our trailers are...

366
00:17:34,357 --> 00:17:36,198
are too long, they're too slow,

367
00:17:36,198 --> 00:17:37,799
and they deliver feeling over function.

368
00:17:37,799 --> 00:17:39,900
But ultimately, they were really successful

369
00:17:39,900 --> 00:17:41,321
precisely for those reasons.

370
00:17:41,321 --> 00:17:44,802
They stood out from a lot of other marketing materials

371
00:17:44,802 --> 00:17:47,444
because of their commitment to the game's identity.

372
00:17:47,444 --> 00:17:49,365
They felt like they were an extension of the game

373
00:17:49,365 --> 00:17:51,305
as opposed to something that was slapped together

374
00:17:51,305 --> 00:17:52,346
after the fact.

375
00:17:52,346 --> 00:17:53,387
And I think that's really important

376
00:17:53,387 --> 00:17:55,788
because what's a marketing material but like an on-ramp,

377
00:17:55,788 --> 00:17:58,089
right, you're trying to pull people in,

378
00:17:58,089 --> 00:18:00,310
and if you're pulling them in in a slapdash way

379
00:18:00,310 --> 00:18:03,591
that doesn't feel genuinely connected to the product itself,

380
00:18:04,052 --> 00:18:07,012
I think you're on ramping them on to a gravel road somewhere.

381
00:18:07,012 --> 00:18:13,914
So the last example I want to bring up is related to game

382
00:18:13,914 --> 00:18:18,955
design. Generally this is a sound principle. Don't just

383
00:18:18,955 --> 00:18:21,636
take away shit from people who worked really hard in your game

384
00:18:21,636 --> 00:18:26,377
to earn it. That's kind of a no brainer. You can kind of see

385
00:18:26,377 --> 00:18:32,518
what we did here. Oh, yeah. Come on to your maker.

386
00:18:34,995 --> 00:18:40,018
What? Oh, my God, I have to choose a hero.

387
00:18:40,018 --> 00:18:40,278
No. Oh, no way.

388
00:18:40,278 --> 00:18:44,781
Oh, it's the cauldron all over again.

389
00:18:44,781 --> 00:18:47,202
No wonder you bring that up.

390
00:18:47,202 --> 00:18:52,365
Oh, wow. Yes.

391
00:18:52,365 --> 00:18:55,266
Shit. Oh, man, we've got the whole boy.

392
00:18:55,266 --> 00:18:59,008
I don't know who to pick.

393
00:18:59,008 --> 00:19:02,310
I feel like we need our healer for the rest of this, but.

394
00:19:07,960 --> 00:19:13,042
Alright, well, we're getting a spare of the others I am ready from our lepers, so I guess

395
00:19:13,042 --> 00:19:15,764
we're gonna send him in.

396
00:19:15,764 --> 00:19:18,765
God damn, that's cold, dude.

397
00:19:18,765 --> 00:19:19,346
Son of a bitch.

398
00:19:19,346 --> 00:19:20,926
Oh my god, come on.

399
00:19:20,926 --> 00:19:26,910
You just, you go through all this and then you just have to give him up.

400
00:19:34,538 --> 00:19:36,959
So that was the final boss for the game.

401
00:19:36,959 --> 00:19:40,561
We violated pretty much every UI, UX rule and game design

402
00:19:40,561 --> 00:19:43,743
rule with that fight precisely to pay off

403
00:19:43,743 --> 00:19:46,544
cosmic horror, incomprehensible cosmic horror,

404
00:19:46,544 --> 00:19:48,845
and the futility of trying to swing a two-handed sword

405
00:19:48,845 --> 00:19:50,066
at the heart of the world.

406
00:19:50,066 --> 00:19:52,567
You can't beat this, right?

407
00:19:52,567 --> 00:19:54,308
How can you beat a Lovecraftian monster?

408
00:19:54,308 --> 00:19:55,369
It's absurd.

409
00:19:55,369 --> 00:19:59,451
So the final boss fight is like a thematic compression

410
00:19:59,451 --> 00:20:00,671
of the entire play experience.

411
00:20:00,671 --> 00:20:02,732
There's all the mechanics feature into that fight.

412
00:20:02,732 --> 00:20:03,753
It's the entire mission.

413
00:20:04,133 --> 00:20:07,074
And death and loss are an important part of our game.

414
00:20:07,074 --> 00:20:09,734
And so we have to kill you in this fight.

415
00:20:09,734 --> 00:20:11,195
Even if you're the best player in the world,

416
00:20:11,195 --> 00:20:13,735
you must die in this fight.

417
00:20:13,735 --> 00:20:15,936
But the first time you play it,

418
00:20:15,936 --> 00:20:17,536
you don't understand what's happening.

419
00:20:17,536 --> 00:20:19,737
We broke the move flow, and you can see,

420
00:20:19,737 --> 00:20:22,198
this is from a streamer called Bitterbit.

421
00:20:22,198 --> 00:20:25,098
You can see he pauses, he's like, I don't understand.

422
00:20:25,098 --> 00:20:27,319
Because the game completely stops doing

423
00:20:27,319 --> 00:20:29,439
what they're used to seeing it do.

424
00:20:29,439 --> 00:20:31,160
And we did that specifically to create

425
00:20:31,160 --> 00:20:32,780
this sense of like, dawning horror.

426
00:20:33,060 --> 00:20:34,401
It's uncertain.

427
00:20:34,401 --> 00:20:35,222
What's going on?

428
00:20:35,222 --> 00:20:37,824
Suddenly now the player is in the position of the heroes

429
00:20:37,824 --> 00:20:38,765
who are in the game.

430
00:20:38,765 --> 00:20:42,889
I mean, it's not as bad for the guy in his computer, right?

431
00:20:42,889 --> 00:20:44,650
But it aligns their expectations,

432
00:20:44,650 --> 00:20:47,032
and suddenly the play field is wide open,

433
00:20:47,032 --> 00:20:48,353
and you're just wracked with uncertainty.

434
00:20:48,353 --> 00:20:49,994
How many more times is he gonna do this?

435
00:20:49,994 --> 00:20:51,215
Is this a death race?

436
00:20:51,215 --> 00:20:52,096
Am I on a timer?

437
00:20:52,096 --> 00:20:54,438
All of these questions kind of swim around,

438
00:20:54,438 --> 00:20:56,260
and it elevates the intensity of the fight,

439
00:20:56,260 --> 00:20:58,381
especially in the final minutes.

440
00:20:58,381 --> 00:20:59,022
Truth be told.

441
00:21:00,206 --> 00:21:02,507
We built it so you could beat this end fight.

442
00:21:02,507 --> 00:21:05,608
We want you to go through this experience,

443
00:21:05,608 --> 00:21:08,810
but we want you to go through it off balance and unsure.

444
00:21:08,810 --> 00:21:11,451
And because that's really what our game has been about.

445
00:21:11,451 --> 00:21:14,112
And we wanted to make that final encounter everything

446
00:21:14,112 --> 00:21:15,032
that we'd been building up to.

447
00:21:15,032 --> 00:21:18,734
So those are some examples of how

448
00:21:18,734 --> 00:21:22,135
we use creative direction practically

449
00:21:22,135 --> 00:21:24,116
throughout the project.

450
00:21:25,994 --> 00:21:27,555
What we do is not easy.

451
00:21:27,555 --> 00:21:28,495
I mean, you guys know this.

452
00:21:28,495 --> 00:21:30,775
There's the hours, there's the pressure,

453
00:21:30,775 --> 00:21:34,076
the desire to do great work as creative people,

454
00:21:34,076 --> 00:21:36,717
not to mention the crushing self-doubt

455
00:21:36,717 --> 00:21:38,718
and financial insecurity,

456
00:21:38,718 --> 00:21:40,038
and all the other sort of horrors

457
00:21:40,038 --> 00:21:42,439
that lurk around in the dark.

458
00:21:42,439 --> 00:21:45,920
But having the confidence that comes from investing early

459
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:48,340
in a strong creative direction for our game

460
00:21:48,340 --> 00:21:50,441
and understanding it, articulating it,

461
00:21:50,441 --> 00:21:52,662
and referencing it in every discussion

462
00:21:52,662 --> 00:21:53,602
that we possibly could.

463
00:21:55,222 --> 00:22:02,250
It gave us a lot of confidence and made our journey a lot easier, I think, than it could have been otherwise.

464
00:22:05,043 --> 00:22:06,664
So we got to know our game.

465
00:22:06,664 --> 00:22:09,465
We externalized its creative core.

466
00:22:09,465 --> 00:22:12,707
We invited it to the meetings.

467
00:22:12,707 --> 00:22:15,269
We leveraged its creative vision to vet features,

468
00:22:15,269 --> 00:22:16,809
to inform decision making.

469
00:22:16,809 --> 00:22:19,291
And the result was, thankfully, a high degree

470
00:22:19,291 --> 00:22:21,812
of creative consistency.

471
00:22:21,812 --> 00:22:24,714
Thematics meshed with art, meshed with sound and audio.

472
00:22:24,714 --> 00:22:26,775
And Stuart Chatwood and Wayne June and Power Up Audio

473
00:22:26,775 --> 00:22:28,996
did a fantastic job on the audio stuff.

474
00:22:30,877 --> 00:22:33,880
everything is in there for a reason. Everything has a

475
00:22:33,880 --> 00:22:36,723
purpose in our game and it can be clearly pointed to. I think

476
00:22:36,723 --> 00:22:39,725
that's really important as an indie game. You can't do

477
00:22:39,725 --> 00:22:42,068
everything but what you do do you have to do it really, really

478
00:22:42,068 --> 00:22:47,493
well to stand out. So... Thanks. I asked him to do like a

479
00:22:47,493 --> 00:22:52,898
Brazilian macaw thing to let me know when I was running out of

480
00:22:52,898 --> 00:22:54,739
time. It was good. It was good. Yeah.

481
00:22:55,751 --> 00:22:59,173
So we spent a long time in early access. We were faced with an

482
00:22:59,173 --> 00:23:03,016
onslaught of fantastic but often times diametrically opposed

483
00:23:03,016 --> 00:23:07,880
feedback. We had our own ideas. We had deadlines. So for a while

484
00:23:07,880 --> 00:23:11,402
there we were mired in the darkest dungeon of development.

485
00:23:11,402 --> 00:23:13,904
But we used our creative direction to illuminate our

486
00:23:13,904 --> 00:23:16,946
decision space a little bit and keep our party focused on what

487
00:23:16,946 --> 00:23:22,130
was important and ultimately we got out intact. Having said

488
00:23:22,130 --> 00:23:25,332
that, I still need a few nights at the tavern. Anyway.

489
00:23:25,460 --> 00:23:26,640
That's my talk. Thank you very much.

490
00:23:26,640 --> 00:23:41,268
I think I timed it okay. I think we have a few minutes for Q&A

491
00:23:41,268 --> 00:23:49,972
if anybody wants to say anything. I have a question.

492
00:23:50,794 --> 00:23:55,941
Yeah, okay, so when you're making a game you sometimes have to pivot your design because you realize it didn't work as well

493
00:23:55,941 --> 00:24:00,387
You did when you separate yourself from your creative direction as its own thing

494
00:24:00,387 --> 00:24:02,991
Is it still able to pivot or you like this is where we have to build now?

495
00:24:03,424 --> 00:24:05,885
I think you want to get to the point where you feel confident

496
00:24:05,885 --> 00:24:09,127
in it before you jump into development so you save

497
00:24:09,127 --> 00:24:10,168
yourself a pivot later.

498
00:24:10,168 --> 00:24:12,349
Obviously, practically sometimes you've got to make

499
00:24:12,349 --> 00:24:13,629
adjustments and changes.

500
00:24:13,629 --> 00:24:16,391
But I think that when you're talking about creative

501
00:24:16,391 --> 00:24:18,552
direction, it can be implemented a number of

502
00:24:18,552 --> 00:24:19,553
different ways.

